{
    "title": "Colour",
    "description": "Colour shapes emotion, hierarchy, accessibility, and brand identity. Understanding how to use colour intentionally is essential for creating interfaces that feel clear, balanced, and trustworthy.",
    "sections": [
        {
            "id": "why-colour-matters",
            "title": "Why Colour Matters",
            "content": [
                {
                    "type": "p",
                    "text": "Colour is one of the strongest tools in visual communication. It influences how users feel, where they look, and how they interpret meaning."
                },
                {
                    "type": "list",
                    "items": [
                        "Creates visual hierarchy",
                        "Communicates meaning (success, warning, error)",
                        "Supports brand identity",
                        "Affects readability and accessibility",
                        "Guides user attention"
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "colour-theory-basics",
            "title": "Colour Theory Basics",
            "content": [
                {
                    "type": "p",
                    "text": "Colour theory helps designers understand how colours relate to each other and how they can be combined effectively."
                },
                {
                    "type": "h3",
                    "text": "Primary Colours"
                },
                {
                    "type": "p",
                    "text": "Red, blue, and yellow — the foundation of all other colours."
                },
                {
                    "type": "h3",
                    "text": "Secondary Colours"
                },
                {
                    "type": "p",
                    "text": "Green, orange, and purple — created by mixing primaries."
                },
                {
                    "type": "h3",
                    "text": "Tertiary Colours"
                },
                {
                    "type": "p",
                    "text": "Colours formed by mixing a primary with a secondary."
                },
                {
                    "type": "h3",
                    "text": "Colour Relationships"
                },
                {
                    "type": "list",
                    "items": [
                        "Complementary — opposite colours (high contrast)",
                        "Analogous — neighbouring colours (harmonious)",
                        "Triadic — evenly spaced colours (balanced)",
                        "Monochromatic — variations of one hue (clean, simple)"
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "colour-in-ui",
            "title": "Colour in UI Design",
            "content": [
                {
                    "type": "p",
                    "text": "In interface design, colour is used less for artistic expression and more for clarity, meaning, and usability."
                },
                {
                    "type": "h3",
                    "text": "Functional Colour"
                },
                {
                    "type": "list",
                    "items": [
                        "Primary colour — main brand or action colour",
                        "Secondary colour — supporting accents",
                        "Success — positive actions or states",
                        "Warning — caution or potential issues",
                        "Error — destructive or invalid actions",
                        "Info — neutral guidance"
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "type": "h3",
                    "text": "Neutral Colours"
                },
                {
                    "type": "p",
                    "text": "Greys, blacks, and whites form the backbone of UI design. They create structure, contrast, and readability."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "contrast-accessibility",
            "title": "Contrast & Accessibility",
            "content": [
                {
                    "type": "p",
                    "text": "Colour must be accessible to all users, including those with low vision or colour vision deficiencies."
                },
                {
                    "type": "list",
                    "items": [
                        "Text should meet WCAG contrast ratios",
                        "Never rely on colour alone to convey meaning",
                        "Use patterns, icons, or labels alongside colour",
                        "Test designs in greyscale to check contrast"
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "text": "WCAG AA contrast:\n- Normal text: 4.5:1\n- Large text: 3:1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "building-a-palette",
            "title": "Building a Colour Palette",
            "content": [
                {
                    "type": "p",
                    "text": "A good palette is intentional, limited, and consistent. Most design systems use a structured palette with clear roles."
                },
                {
                    "type": "h3",
                    "text": "A typical palette includes:"
                },
                {
                    "type": "list",
                    "items": [
                        "Primary colour",
                        "Secondary colour",
                        "Neutral greys",
                        "Semantic colours (success, warning, error)",
                        "Background and surface colours"
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "type": "h3",
                    "text": "Best Practices"
                },
                {
                    "type": "list",
                    "items": [
                        "Limit your palette to avoid visual noise",
                        "Use tints and shades for depth",
                        "Ensure consistent contrast across surfaces",
                        "Document colour usage rules clearly"
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}
